<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-083-384 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 100 517  OV: 11 100 319.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 12 1991 v8 n32 p72(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lasergrpahics Inc.: LFR. (Hardware Review) (one of fiveevaluations of film recorders in 'Slide makers put on a goodshow') (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Caton, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Lasergraphics Inc's LFR film recorder prints sharp slides withconsistent focusing but has trouble with horizontally orvertically ramped images.andP;  Its Rascol II software works with arasterizing board based on a Motorola 68000 processor; the boardand software are included in the base price of $8,950.andP;  A unitconfigured for the Macintosh costs $8,750; a configuration withsupport for both systems is $10,595, and a camera back costs$1,495.andP;  Users must run a software installation program beforeinstalling the add-in board.andP;  Lasergraphics' Opts menu-drivenvector graphics utility lets users select a wide variety ofoptions; the MacRascol software for the Macintosh supports PICT,PICT II and Scrapbook files.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lasergraphics Inc. (Products).andO;Product:   Lasergraphics LFR (Film recorder) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     Film RecordersEvaluationI/O Devices.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Vital signs. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Lasergraphics Inc.andM;LFRandM;The Lasergraphics LFR film recorder printed sharp, well-focused slides, yetit had difficulty in reproducing vertically and horizontally ramped images.andM;The test images reproduced by the LFR in PC Week Labs tests were in focus,and details at the edge of the image were not lost.andP;  However, banding marredthe LFR's red-green-blue (RGB) and gray-to-black ramp test images.andP;  Thevertical ramp test of five different-colored bars also showed some banding asthe colors faded to black.andM;The LFR also tends to shift to black in ramped images toward the middle ofthe image.andM;The Lasergraphic LFR's software, Rascol II, is identical to the software usedwith the Montage recorder, and both products use a rasterizing board based onthe Motorola Corp.andP;  68000 processor.andP;  Each product uses a different filmrecorder and camera back, and the LFR's board came with more memory than theMontage board.andM;The Lasergraphics LFR film recorder for DOS costs $8,950, including theRascol II board and software.andP;  A Macintosh version of the product costs$8,750.andP;  PC Week Labs tested a Mac-based system with the Rascol II boards andsoftware.andP;  A camera back for printing instant transparencies and film costs$1,495.andM;File formats accepted by the LFR's Rascol software for DOS includeLasergraphics Language (LL), an image-description protocol, Hewlett-PackardGraphics Language (HPGL) and TARGA.andM;Before installing the add-in board, users must run the software installationprogram.andP;  This identifies how the jumpers on the board must be set so thatthe board can be configured as a second or third parallel port.andM;Opts, the menu-driven utility for vector graphics, allows users to selectresolution, film type, file format, plotter type and pen colors.andP;  Users mustthen copy a file to the parallel port that drives the film recorder.andP;  Rioptsis the utility for raster graphics that allows TARGA files to be copieddirectly to the film recorder.andM;The software for the Macintosh, MacRascol, allows users to line up PICT, PICTII or Scrapbook files in a queue to be printed later.andM;To test the print speed of the LFR, the image was printed from within HarvardGraphics.andP;  The Lasergraphics LFR scored in the middle of the products tested,printing the image in about 2 minutes.andM;------------------&quot;VITAL SIGNS&quot; DATAandM;Lasergraphics Inc.andM;Irvine, Calif.andP;  (714) 727-2651andM;Privately heldandM;Year established: 1981andM;Number of employees: 55andM;Gross annual revenueandM;and earnings: Not disclosedandM;Source.andP;  Information supplied by company.andM;</TEXT></DOC>